## Quick Reference Diagram (UML)

Below is a **simplified class diagram** that ties all five principles together. The arrows point from high‑level modules to the abstractions they depend on (DIP), and each abstraction is kept **lean** (ISP). Concrete implementations can be added without editing the high‑level classes (OCP). The hierarchy (`Shape` → `Rectangle`/`Square`) respects LSP, and every class has a single responsibility.

```
+---------------------------+          +-------------------+
|        OrderProcessor     |<>------->| IOrderRepository  |
|  (high‑level)             |          | (abstraction)    |
+---------------------------+          +-------------------+
   ^          ^          ^                     ^
   |          |          |                     |
   |          |          |                     |
   |          |          |                     |
   |          |          |                     |
   |          |          |   +-----------------+-----------------+
   |          |          |   |                                   |
   |          |          |   |                                   |
   |          |          |   |                                   |
   |          |          |   |                                   |
   |          |          |   |                                   |
+----------+ +----------+ +--------------+   +-------------------+
| IOrder   | | IOrder   | | IOrderNotifier|   | SqlOrderRepository|
| Validator| | Repository| | (email)       |   | (implements IOrd)|
+----------+ +----------+ +--------------+   +-------------------+
      ^           ^           ^                     ^
      |           |           |                     |
+------------+ +------------+ +---------------+ +------------+
| OrderValidator| | SqlOrderRepo| | EmailNotify | | InMemoryRepo|
+------------+ +------------+ +---------------+ +------------+

--- Shape hierarchy (LSP) ---
+------------+
|   Shape    |
+------------+
   ^    ^
   |    |
+-------+------+
| Rectangle   |   (immutable ⇒ SRP, OCP)
+------------+    
| Square      |
+------------+
```

*Key*:  
* **`<>`** denotes “depends on” (via constructor injection – DIP).  
* Each concrete class (e.g., `SqlOrderRepository`) **implements a single interface**, never the other way around (ISP).  
* Adding a new notification method (`SmsNotificationService`) or a new discount (`HolidayDiscount`) means **creating a new class** that implements the existing interface – no modification of existing code (OCP).  
* The `Shape` hierarchy shows **correct LSP** – derived types preserve the contract of the base (`Area`).  

---  

## TL;DR Checklist

| Principle | ✅ Correct Design | ❌ Typical Mistake |
|-----------|-------------------|-------------------|
| **SRP**   | One class = one reason to change. | “God” class that does everything. |
| **OCP**   | Extend by adding new implementations; existing code untouched. | Adding new `if`/`switch` branches inside core classes. |
| **LSP**   | Substitutable objects behave exactly as the base contract promises. | Overriding methods with side‑effects that break expectations. |
| **ISP**   | Small, role‑specific interfaces. | Large “everything” interface that forces unused members. |
| **DIP**   | High‑level modules depend on abstractions; concrete details are injected. | Direct `new ConcreteX()` inside business logic. |

When you keep these rules in mind while designing your classes, you’ll end up with **code that is easier to understand, test, maintain, and extend**—exactly what solid object‑oriented design strives for. Happy coding!

